# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcohol-in-indonesia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh is where the spread of Islam in Indonesia began.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] It was a key location for the spread of Islam in Southeast Asia more broadly.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Islam reached Aceh (Kingdoms of Fansur and Lamuri) around 1250.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In the early 17th century, the Aceh Sultanate was the wealthiest, most powerful, and most cultivated state in the Strait of Malacca.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh has a history of political independence and resistance to control by outsiders, including the former Dutch East Indies and later the Indonesian governments.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh has substantial natural resources of oil and natural gas.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh was the closest point of land to the epicenter of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, which devastated much of the western coast of the province.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Approximately 170,000 Indonesians were killed or went missing in the disaster.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The disaster helped precipitate the peace agreement between the government of Indonesia and the separatist group of Free Aceh Movement.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Upon its formation in 1956 it bore the name **Aceh** before being renamed to the **Daerah Istimewa Aceh** (Special Region of Aceh; 1959–2001), **Nanggroe Aceh Darussalam** (2001–2009), and back to **Aceh** (2009–present).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In the past it was also spelled as *Acheh*, *Atjeh*, and *Achin*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] According to several archaeological findings, the first evidence of human habitation in Aceh is from a site near the Tamiang River, where shell middens are present.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Stone tools and faunal remains were also found on the site.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Archeologists believe the site was first occupied around 10,000 BCE.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The history of Aceh stretches back to the Lambri Kingdom.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Several documented references indicate that Hindu-Buddhist culture existed in the area before its Islamization.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The people of Lambri were described by Marco Polo as "idolaters", who had a maharaja as their ruler (a king in the Hindu political structure), likely meaning they were Hindus, Buddhists, or a combination thereof.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The inscription at Tanjore of Rajendra I documents the conquest of a land called "llämuridesam", located at the northern tip of Sumatra.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The *Nagarakretagama* documents the possessions of the Imperial Majapahit and states that it controls Barat (identified as the western coast of Aceh).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Chinese records indicate that Aceh was under the control of the Sriwijaya.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Though many temples were left abandoned or converted into mosques, such as the Indrapuri Old Mosque, some evidence remains, such as the head of a stone sculpture of Avalokiteshvara Boddhisattva that was discovered in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Images of Amitabha Buddhas adorn his crown, facing forward and on each side.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Srivijayan art estimated 9th-century CE collection of National Museum of Indonesia, Jakarta.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] One of the few remaining structures is the Indra Patra fort, which houses several Hindu shrines.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Historic names such as Indrapurba, Indrapurwa, Indrapatra, and Indrapuri, which refer to the god Indra, also indicate that Hinduism had a lasting and significant presence in this land.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Evidence concerning the arrival and subsequent establishment of Islam in Southeast Asia is thin and inconclusive.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The historian Anthony Reid has argued that the region of the Cham people on the south-central coast of Vietnam was one of the earliest Islamic centers in Southeast Asia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Furthermore, as the Cham people fled the Vietnamese, one of the earliest locations where they established a relationship was with Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] It is thought that one of the earliest centers of Islam was in the Aceh region.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] When Venetian traveler Marco Polo passed by Sumatra on his way home from China in 1292, he found that Peureulak was a Muslim town while nearby "Basma(n)" and "Samara" were not.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] "Basma(n)" and "Samara" are often said to be Pasai and Samudra, but evidence is inconclusive.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The gravestone of Sultan Malikussaleh, the first Muslim ruler of Samudra, has been found and is dated AH 696 (1297 CE).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This is the earliest clear evidence of a Muslim dynasty in the Indonesia-Malay area, and more 13th-century gravestones show that this region continued under Muslim rule.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Ibn Batutah, a Moroccan traveller, passing through on his way to China in 1345 and 1346, found that the ruler of Samudra was a follower of the Shafi'i school of Islam.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] After Islam first appeared in Aceh, it spread into the coastal regions by the 15th century.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh soon became a cultural and scholastic Islamic center throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] It also became wealthy because it was a center of extensive trade.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Portuguese apothecary Tome Pires reported in his early 16th-century book *Suma Oriental* that most of the kings of Sumatra, from Aceh to Palembang, were Muslim.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] At Pasai, in what is now the North Aceh Regency, there was a thriving international port.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Pires attributed the establishment of Islam in Pasai to the 'cunning' of the Muslim merchants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The ruler of Pasai, however, had not been able to convert the people of the interior.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Sultanate of Aceh was established by Sultan Ali Mughayat Syah in 1511.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] João Ribeiro Gaio, based on information provided by a former captive called Diogo Gil, wrote the "Roteiro das Cousas do Achem" (Lisboa 1997)—a description of the sultanate.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Later, during its golden era, in the 17th century, its territory and political influence expanded as far as Satun in southern Thailand, Johor in Malay Peninsula, and Siak in what is today the province of Riau.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As was the case with most non-Javan pre-colonial states, Acehnese power expanded outward by sea rather than inland.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As it expanded down the Sumatran coast, its main competitors were Johor and Portuguese Malacca on the other side of the Straits of Malacca.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] It was this seaborne trade focus that led Aceh to rely on rice imports from north Java rather than develop self-sufficiency in rice production.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] After the Portuguese occupation of Malacca in 1511, many Islamic traders passing the Malacca Straits shifted their trade to Banda Aceh and increased the Acehnese rulers' wealth.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During the reign of Sultan Iskandar Muda in the 17th century, Aceh's influence extended to most of Sumatra and the Malay Peninsula.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh allied itself with the Ottoman Empire and the Dutch East India Company in their struggle against the Portuguese and the Johor Sultanate.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Acehnese military power waned gradually thereafter, and Aceh ceded its territory of Pariaman in Sumatra to the Dutch in the 18th century.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] By the early 19th century, however, Aceh had become an increasingly influential power due to its strategic location for controlling regional trade.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In the 1820s, it was the producer of over half the world's supply of black pepper.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The pepper trade produced new wealth for the sultanate and for the rulers of many smaller nearby ports that had been under Aceh's control, but were now able to assert more independence.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] These changes initially threatened Aceh's integrity, but a new Sultan, Tuanku Ibrahim, who ruled from 1838 to 1870, reasserted control over nearby ports.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Under the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1824, the British ceded their colonial possessions on Sumatra to the Dutch.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In the treaty, the British described Aceh as one of their possessions, although they had no actual control over the sultanate.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Initially, under the agreement, the Dutch agreed to respect Aceh's independence.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 1871, however, the British dropped previous opposition to a Dutch invasion of Aceh, possibly to prevent France or the United States from gaining a foothold in the region.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Although neither the Dutch nor the British knew the specifics, there had been rumors since the 1850s that Aceh had been in communication with the rulers of France and of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Pirates operating from Aceh threatened commerce in the Strait of Malacca; the sultan was unable to control them.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Britain was a protector of Aceh and permitted the Netherlands to eradicate the pirates.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The campaign quickly drove out the sultan, but the local leaders mobilized and fought the Dutch in four decades of guerrilla war, with high levels of atrocities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Dutch colonial government declared war on Aceh on 26 March 1873.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh sought American help, but Washington rejected the request.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Dutch tried one strategy after another over the course of four decades.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] An expedition under Major General Johan Harmen Rudolf Köhler in 1873 occupied most of the coastal areas.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Köhler's strategy was to attack and take the sultan's palace.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Dutch then tried a naval blockade, reconciliation, concentration within a line of forts, and lastly passive containment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Reaching 15 to 20 million guilders a year, the heavy spending for failed strategies nearly bankrupted the colonial government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During the course of the war, the Dutch set up the Gouvernment of Atjeh and Dependencies under a governor, although it did not establish wider control of its territory until after 1908.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Aceh army was rapidly modernized, and Aceh soldiers killed Köhler.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Köhler made some grave tactical errors, and the reputation of the Dutch was severely harmed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In recent years, in line with expanding international attention to human rights issues and atrocities in war zones, there has been increasing discussion about some of the recorded acts of cruelty and slaughter committed by Dutch troops during the period of warfare in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Hasan Mustafa (1852–1930) was a chief *penghulu* (judge) for the colonial government, stationed in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] He had to balance traditional Muslim justice with Dutch law.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] To stop the Aceh rebellion, Hasan Mustafa issued a fatwa, telling the Muslim population there in 1894, "It is Incumbent upon the Indonesian Muslim to be loyal to the Dutch East Indies Government".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During World War II, Japanese troops occupied Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Acehnese *ulama* (Islamic clerics) fought against both the Dutch and the Japanese, revolting against the Dutch in February 1942 and against Japan in November 1942.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The revolt was led by the All-Aceh Religious Scholars' Association (PUSA).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Japanese suffered 18 dead in the uprising while they slaughtered up to 100 or over 120 Acehnese.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The revolt happened in Bayu and was centered around Tjot Plieng village's religious school.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During the revolt, the Japanese troops armed with mortars and machine guns were charged by sword wielding Acehnese under Teungku Abduldjalil (Tengku Abdul Djalil) in Buloh Gampong Teungah and Tjot Plieng on 10 and 13 November.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In May 1945 the Acehnese rebelled again.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The religious ulama party gained ascendancy to replace district warlords (*ulèebalang*) party that formerly collaborated with the Dutch.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Concrete bunkers still line the northernmost beaches.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] After World War II, civil war erupted in 1945 between the district warlords party, which supported the return of a Dutch government, and the Persatuan Ulama Seluruh Aceh (PUSA) party, which supported the newly proclaimed state of Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The ulama won, and the area remained free during the Indonesian War of Independence.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Dutch military itself never attempted to invade Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The civil war raised the religious *ulama* party leader, Daud Bereu'eh, to the position of military governor of Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Acehnese revolted soon after their inclusion into an independent Indonesia, a situation created by a complex mix of what the Acehnese regarded as transgressions against and betrayals of their rights.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Sukarno, the first president of Indonesia, had reneged on his promise made on 16 June 1948 that Aceh would be allowed to rule itself in accordance with Islamic Law.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh was politically dismantled and incorporated into the province of North Sumatra in 1950.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This resulted in the Acehnese Rebellion of 1953–59, which was led by Daud Beureu'eh, who on 20 September 1953 declared a free, independent Aceh under the leadership of Sekarmadji Maridjan Kartosoewirjo.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 1959, the Indonesian government attempted to placate the Acehnese by offering broad freedom in matters of religion, education, and culture.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During the 1970s, under an agreement with the Indonesian central government, American oil and gas companies began the exploitation of Aceh's natural resources.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Alleged unequal distribution of profits between the central government and the native people of Aceh induced Dr.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Hasan Muhammad di Tiro, former ambassador of Darul Islam, to call for an independent Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The movement had a small number of followers initially, and di Tiro himself had to live in exile in Sweden.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Meanwhile, the province followed Suharto's policy of economic development and industrialization.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During the late 1980s, several security incidents prompted the Indonesian central government to take repressive measures and to send troops to Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Human rights abuse was rampant for the next decade, resulting in many grievances on the part of the Acehnese toward the Indonesian central government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 1990, the Indonesian government initiated military operations against GAM by deploying more than 12,000 Indonesian troops in the region.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] During the late 1990s, chaos in Java and an ineffective central government gave an advantage to the Free Aceh Movement and resulted in the second phase of the rebellion, this time with large support from the Acehnese people.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This support was demonstrated during the 1999 plebiscite in Banda Aceh, which was attended by nearly half a million people (out of the province's four million population).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Indonesian central government responded in 2001 by broadening Aceh's autonomy, giving its government the right to apply Sharia law more broadly and the right to receive direct foreign investment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This was again accompanied by repressive measures, however, and in 2003 an offensive began and a state of emergency was proclaimed in the province.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The war was still ongoing when the tsunami disaster of 2004 struck the province.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2001, villagers from the North Aceh Regency sued ExxonMobil for human rights abuses at the hands of Indonesian military units hired by the company for security for its natural gas operations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] ExxonMobil denied fault for the allegations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] After a series of attacks against its operations, the company shut down its Arun natural gas operations in the province.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The western coastal areas of Aceh, including the cities of Banda Aceh, Calang, and Meulaboh, were among the areas hardest hit by the tsunami resulting from the magnitude 9.2 Indian Ocean earthquake on 26 December 2004.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] While estimates vary, over 170,000 people were killed by the tsunami in Aceh, and about 500,000 were left homeless.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The tragedy of the tsunami was further compounded several months later, when the 2005 M8.6 Nias–Simeulue earthquake struck the seabed between the islands of Simeulue Island in Aceh and Nias in North Sumatra.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This second quake killed a further 1346 people on Nias and Simeulue, displaced tens of thousands more, and caused the tsunami response to be expanded to include Nias.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The World Health Organisation estimates a 100% increase in prevalence of mild and moderate mental disorders in Aceh's general population after the tsunami.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center, misjudging the intensity of the Sumatra earthquake, issued a bulletin stating that no tsunami was expected following a magnitude 8.0 quake, based on historical data.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Only when more accurate measurements of quakes of magnitude 9.0 or higher became available did scientists at the warning center realize they were dealing with a basin-wide tsunami across the Indian Ocean.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] When the tsunami hit, it was enormous, and the death toll in Aceh exceeded 100,000.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] There was no tsunami warning system in 2004.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Tsunami warning systems have improved since the immense death toll drew international attention, but in rural areas where many lack internet access or cell phones, it remains a challenge to communicate warnings promptly.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] A warning system was put in place at the request of Aceh residents, but it was disabled in 2007 after technical issues and a false alarm that caused a panic.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The population of Aceh before the December 2004 tsunami was 4,271,000 (2004).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As of February 2006, more than a year after the tsunami, a large number of people were still living in barrack-style temporary living centers (TLC) or tents.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Reconstruction was visible everywhere, but due to the sheer scale of the disaster and logistic difficulties, progress was slow.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] A study in 2007 estimated that 83.6% of the population had a psychiatric illness, while 69.8% suffers from severe emotional distress.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The ramifications of the tsunami went beyond the immediate impact on the lives and infrastructure of the Acehnese living on the coast.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Since the disaster, the Acehnese rebel movement GAM, which had been fighting for independence against the Indonesian authorities for 29 years, has signed a peace deal (15 August 2005).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The perception that the tsunami was punishment for insufficient piety in this proudly Muslim province is partly behind the increased emphasis on the importance of religion post-tsunami.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This has been most evident in the increased implementation of Sharia law, including the introduction of the controversial Wilayatul Hisbah (Syariah police).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As homes are being built and people's basic needs are met, the people are also looking to improve the quality of education, increase tourism, and develop a responsible, sustainable industry.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Well-qualified educators are in high demand in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] While parts of the capital Banda Aceh were unscathed, the areas closest to the water, especially the areas of Kampung Jawa and Meuraxa, were completely destroyed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Most of the rest of the western coast of Aceh was severely damaged.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Other towns on Aceh's west coast hit by the disaster included Lhoknga, Leupung, Lamno, Patek, Calang, Teunom, and the island of Simeulue.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Affected or destroyed towns on the region's north and east coasts were Pidie Regency, Samalanga, and Lhokseumawe.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The area was slowly rebuilt after the disaster.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The government initially proposed the creation of a two-kilometer buffer zone along low-lying coastal areas within which permanent construction was not permitted.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This proposal was unpopular among some local residents and proved impractical in most situations, especially among fishing families that depend on living near the sea.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Indonesian government established a special agency for Aceh reconstruction, the Badan Rehabilitasi dan Rekonstruksi (BRR), headed by Kuntoro Mangkusubroto, a former Indonesian government minister.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This agency had ministry-level authority and incorporated officials, professionals, and community leaders from all backgrounds.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Most of the reconstruction work was performed by local people using a mix of traditional methods and partially prefabricated structures, with funding from many international organizations, governments, and individuals, as well as the people themselves.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Government of Indonesia estimated in their Preliminary Damage and Losses Assessment that damages amounted to US$4.5 billion (before inflation, and US$6.2 billion including inflation).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Three years after the tsunami, reconstruction was still ongoing.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The World Bank monitored funding for reconstruction in Aceh and reported that US$7.7 billion had been earmarked for the reconstruction, whilst in June 2007, US$5.8 billion had been allocated to specific reconstruction projects, of which US$3.4 billion had actually been spent (58%).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2009, the government opened a US$5.6 million museum to commemorate the tsunami with photographs, stories, and a simulation of the earthquake that triggered the tsunami.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The 2004 tsunami helped trigger a peace agreement between the GAM and the Indonesian government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The mood in post-Suharto Indonesia during the liberal-democratic reform period, along with changes in the Indonesian military, helped create an environment more favorable to peace talks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The roles of newly elected president Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono and vice president Jusuf Kalla were highly significant.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] At the same time, the GAM leadership was undergoing changes, and the Indonesian military had inflicted so much damage on the rebel movement that it had little choice but to negotiate with the central government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The peace talks were first initiated by Juha Christensen, a Finnish peace activist, and then formally facilitated by a Finland-based NGO, the Crisis Management Initiative led by former Finnish president Martti Ahtisaari.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The resulting peace agreement, generally known as the Helsinki Agreement, was signed on 15 August 2005.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Under the agreement, Aceh would receive special autonomy, and government troops would be withdrawn from the province in exchange for GAM's disarmament.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As part of the agreement, the European Union dispatched Aceh Monitoring Mission.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Their mission expired on 15 December 2006, following local elections.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh has been granted greater autonomy through an Aceh government law that includes special rights agreed in 2006 as well as the right of Acehnese people to establish local political parties to represent their interests.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Human rights advocates protest that previous human rights violations in the province have not been seriously addressed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2014, there were 460 Sumatran elephants in Aceh including at least eight baby elephants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The area has been suffering from deforestation since the 1970s.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The first wood pulp mill in Aceh was built in 1982.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The government of Aceh intends a law by which 1.2 million hectares would be opened for commercial use.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Coastal waters off Aceh fall within Fisheries Management Area 572 (WPP 572), where the Blue Halo S pilot—involving Konservasi Indonesia—has focused on improving marine management and resilience outcomes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Within the country, Aceh is governed not as a regular province but as a special autonomous province (*daerah istimewa*), an administrative designation intended to give the area increased autonomy from the central government in Jakarta.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This has resulted in canings for crimes deemed to have violated *Sharia*, such as gambling, drinking, skipping Friday prayers, and most notably homosexuality.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Regional elections have been held in Aceh in recent years for senior positions at the provincial, regency (*kabupaten*) and district (*kecamatan*) levels.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In the 2006 elections, Irwandi Yusuf was elected as the provincial governor for 2007–2012; in the elections in April 2012, Zaini Abdullah was elected as governor for 2012–2017.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Beginning with the promulgation of Law 44/1999, Aceh's governor began to issue limited *Sharia*-based regulations—for example, requiring female government employees to wear Islamic dress.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The frequency of attacks on individuals considered to be violating shariatic principles appeared to increase following the enactment of Law 44/1999 and the governor's *Sharia* regulations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2014, a group of scholars calling themselves the *Tadzkiiratul Ummah* began attacking and painting the pants of men and women as a call for heavier Islamic law enforcement in the area.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Upon the enactment of the Special Autonomy Law in 2001, Aceh's provincial legislature enacted a series of *qanuns* (local laws) governing the implementation of *Sharia*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] With the exception of gambling, none of the practices are prohibited outside of Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Responsibility for enforcement of the *qanun*s rests both with the Indonesian National Police and with a special Islamic religious police force unique to Aceh known as the Wilayatul Hisbah (Sharia Authority).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] All of the *qanun*s provide for penalties including fines, imprisonment, and caning, the latter a punishment unknown in most parts of Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Between mid-2005 and early 2007, at least 135 people were caned in Aceh for transgressing the *qanun*s.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In April 2016, a 60-year-old non-Muslim woman was sentenced to 30 lashes for selling alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The controversy was *qanun* enforcement did not apply to non-Muslims, with only national law, as in the rest of Indonesia, applying.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In April 2009, the Aceh Party won control of the local parliament in Aceh's first post-war legislative elections.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In September 2009, one month before the new legislators were to take office, the outgoing parliament unanimously endorsed two new *qanun*s to expand the existing criminal *Sharia* framework in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] One bill, the *Qanun on Criminal Procedure* (*Qanun Hukum Jinayat*), was intended to create an entirely new procedural code for the enforcement of *Sharia* by police, prosecutors, and courts in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The law authorized punishments, including up to 60 lashes for "intimacy," up to 100 lashes for engaging in homosexual conduct, up to 100 lashes for adultery by unmarried persons, and death by stoning for adultery by a married person.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] However, the then-proposed laws were met with widespread condemnation across Indonesia, and then-governor Irwandi Yusuf refused to sign them, thereby leaving them without legal force, rather than actual laws.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In March 2013, the Aceh government removed the stoning provision from its own draft of a new criminal code.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In practice, since the introduction of the new laws, there has been a considerable increase in the use of the allowable penalties.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As an example, in August 2015, six men in Bireuën Regency were arrested and caned for betting on the names of passing buses.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] On 18 September 2015, a total of 34 people were caned in Banda Aceh and in the nearby regency of Aceh Besar.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Two gay men are to be publicly lashed 85 times each under *Sharia* law after being filmed by vigilantes in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] An Islamic court in the province of Aceh passed down its first sentence for homosexuality on the International Day Against Homophobia and Transphobia, 17 May 2017, in spite of international appeals to spare the couple.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Whipping is the common *hudud* punishment for gambling, adultery, drinking alcohol, and having gay or premarital sex.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Typically, the whipping has been done by men.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2020, with increased enforcement and more crimes being committed by women, Aceh authorities noted the government was trying to follow Islamic law, which calls for women to be whipped by female perpetrators.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Administratively, the province is subdivided into eighteen regencies (Indonesian: *kabupaten*; Acehnese: *kabupatèn*) and five autonomous cities (Indonesian: *kota*; Acehnese: *banda*).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The capital and the largest city is Banda Aceh, located on the coast near the northern tip of Sumatra.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] When originally devised in 1956, the province comprised the city of Banda Aceh and six regencies: Great Aceh, Pidie, North Aceh, East Aceh, Central Aceh, and West Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] However, on 14 November 1956, a seventh regency (South Aceh) was created from the southeastern districts of West Aceh Regency.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Bener Meriah Regency was created on 19 December 2003 (from part of Central Aceh Regency), and Pidie Jaya Regency (from part of Pidie Regency) and Subulussalam City (from part of Aceh Singkil Regency) on 2 January 2007.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Some other local areas are pushing to create new autonomous areas, usually with the stated goal of enhancing local control over politics and development.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The cities and regencies (subdivided into the 289 districts or *kecamatan* of Aceh), are listed below with their areas and their populations at the 2010 census and the 2020 census, together with the officially estimated population as of mid 2024.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh is unique in Indonesia in grouping its villages into *mukim*s.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] These are sometimes related to traditional indigenous communities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Beginning in September 2023, the Indonesian government provided legal recognition to the claims of some *mukim*s over customary forests.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The province comprises two of Indonesia's 84 national electoral districts to elect members to the People's Representative Council.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2006, the economy of Aceh grew by 7.7% after having minimal growth since the devastating tsunami.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This growth was primarily driven by the reconstruction effort with massive growth in the building/construction sector.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The ending of the conflict, and the reconstruction program resulted in the structure of the economy changing significantly since 2003.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Service sectors played a more dominant role whilst the share of the oil and gas sectors continued to decline.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] After peaking at around 40% in December 2005, largely as a result of the Dutch disease impact of sudden aid flows into the province, inflation declined steadily and was 8.5% in June 2007, close to the national level in Indonesia of 5.7%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Persistent inflation means that Aceh's consumer price index (CPI) remains the highest in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] As a result, Aceh's cost competitiveness has declined as reflected in both inflation and wage data.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Although inflation has slowed down, CPI has registered steady increases since the tsunami.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Using 2002 as a base, Aceh's CPI increased to 185.6 (June 2007) while the national CPI increased to 148.2.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] There have been relatively large nominal wage increases in particular sectors, such as construction where, on average, workers' nominal wages have risen to almost Rp.60,000 per day, from Rp.29,000 pre-tsunami.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This is also reflected in Aceh's minimum regional wage (UMR, or Upah Minimum Regional), which increased by 55% from Rp.550,000 pre-tsunami to Rp.850,000 in 2007, compared with an increase of 42% in neighboring North Sumatra, from Rp.537,000 to Rp.761,000.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Poverty levels increased slightly in Aceh in 2005 after the tsunami, but by less than expected.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The poverty level then fell in 2006 to below the pre-tsunami level, suggesting that the rise in tsunami-related poverty was short lived and reconstruction activities and the end of the conflict most probably facilitated this decline.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] However, poverty in Aceh remains significantly higher than in the rest of Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] A large number of the Acehnese remain vulnerable to poverty, reinforcing the need for further sustained efforts at development in the post-tsunami construction period.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The population of Aceh was not adequately documented during the Indonesia 2000 census because the insurgency complicated the process of collecting accurate information.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] An estimated 170,000 people died in Aceh in the 2004 tsunami which further complicates the task of careful demographic analysis.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The official estimate for mid 2023 was 5,482,527 (comprising 2,753,176 males and 2,729,351 females); however, the sum of the official population estimates for the individual regencies and cities totalled 5,512,219 people.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh is a diverse region occupied by several ethnic and language groups.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] There are also significant populations of Chinese and Javanese.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Among the present-day population of Aceh, especially in coastal areas, one can find a number of individuals of Arab, Turkish, Portuguese, and Indian descent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Acehnese language is widely spoken within the Acehnese population.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This is a member of the Aceh-Chamic group of languages, whose other representatives are mostly found in Vietnam and Cambodia, and is also closely related to the Malay group of languages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Acehnese also has many words borrowed from Malay and Arabic and traditionally was written using Arabic script.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Acehnese is also used as local language in Langkat and Asahan (North Sumatra), and Kedah (Malaysia), and once dominated Penang.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aside from the Indonesian language, Acehnese is also designated as the co-official regional language of Aceh under Qanun Number 10 of 2022.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Alas and Kluet are closely related languages within the Batak group.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Jamee language originated from Minangkabau language in West Sumatra, with just a few variations and differences.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] According to 2022 data of the Ministry of Religious Affairs, Aceh is overwhelmingly Muslim-majority where they dominate Aceh with more than 98%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] While the rest 1.15% of population are Protestants, 0.13% Buddhists and 0.1% Catholics.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Religious issues are often sensitive in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] There is very strong support for Islam across the province, and sometimes other religious groups – such as Christians or Buddhists – feel that they are subject to social or community pressure to limit their activities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The official explanation for this action, supported by both the governor of Aceh Zaini Abdullah and the Indonesian home affairs minister Gamawan Fauzi from Jakarta, was that the churches did not have the appropriate permits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Earlier in April 2012, a number of churches in the Singkil regency in southern Aceh had also been ordered to close.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In response, some Christians voiced concern about these actions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2015 a church was burned down and another attacked in which a Muslim rioter was shot, causing President Joko Widodo to call for calm.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Caning has increasingly been used as a form of judicial punishment in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] At least 72 people were caned for various offences, including drinking alcohol, being alone with someone of the opposite sex who was not a marriage partner or relative (khalwat), gambling and for being caught having gay sex.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The Acehnese authorities passed a series of by-laws governing the implementation of Sharia after the enactment of the province's Special Autonomy Law in 2001.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 2016 alone, 100 public caning cases were documented by human rights organizations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In January 2018, the Aceh police, with support from the Aceh autonomous government, raided hair salons known to have LGBT clients and staff as part of an *operasi penyakit masyarakat* ("community sickness operation").
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The police abused all LGBT citizens within the premises of the parlors and arrested twelve transgender women.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The arrested trans women were stripped topless, had their heads shaved, and were forced to chant insults at themselves as part of a process "until they really become men".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The intent of the incident was to reverse what officials deemed a "social disease" and that parents were coming to them upset at the increasing number of LGBT individuals in Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The event was decried by human rights organizations local and worldwide, such as Amnesty International.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh has many tourist destinations, especially natural, historical and cultural tourism.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh has a variety of distinctive arts and culture.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In addition to rencong, the Acehnese people also possessed several other special weapons, such as sikin panyang, peurise awe, peurise teumaga, siwah, geuliwang and peudeueng.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh's traditional house is called *Rumoh Aceh*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] This house is a type of house on stilts with three main parts and one additional section.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The three main parts of the Aceh house are the *seuramoë keuë* (front porch), *seuramoë teungoh* (middle porch) and *seuramoë likôt* (back porch).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Another additional part is the *rumoh dapu* (kitchen house).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Traditional Acehnese dances illustrate traditional heritage, religion, and local folklore.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Acehnese dances are generally performed in groups, in which a group of dancers are of the same sex, and there are standing or sitting positions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] When viewed from the accompanying music, the dances can be grouped into two types; namely accompanied by the vocal and percussion of the dancer's own body, and accompanied by an ensemble of musical instruments.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Some dances that are famous at the national and even world level are dances originating from Aceh, such as the Rateb Meuseukat Dance and the Saman dance.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Acehnese cuisine uses combinations of spices found in Indian and Arabic cuisine, include ginger, pepper, coriander, cumin, cloves, cinnamon, cardamom, and fennel.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] A variety of Acehnese foods are cooked with curry or curry spices and coconut milk, which are generally combined with meat, such as buffalo meat, beef, lamb, fish and chicken.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Certain recipes have traditionally used cannabis as a seasoning; which is also found in some other Southeast Asian dishes such as in Laos, but now the material is no longer used.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Dishes native to Aceh include nasi gurih, mie aceh, mie caluk and timphan.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Aceh has a tradition of oral literature, such as the folktales *The king of the parakeets* and *Banta Berensyah*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The oldest Acehnese manuscripts that can be found are from 1069 H (1658/1659 AD), namely Hikayat Seuma'un.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Before Dutch colonialism (1873–1942), almost all Acehnese literature was in the form of poetry known as Hikayat.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Very little is in the form of prose and one of them is the Book of Bakeu Meunan which is a translation of the book Qawaa'id al-Islaam.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] It was only after the arrival of the Dutch that Acehnese writings appeared in the form of prose, in the 1930s, such as Lhee Saboh Nang written by Aboe Bakar and De Vries.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] It was only afterward that various forms of prose appeared, but still remained dominated by the form of Hikayat.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] The 74-km Sigli–Banda Aceh Toll Road is currently under construction, as a part of the Trans-Sumatra Toll Road.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Railways in Aceh has started since the Dutch colonial era.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] In 1876 the Royal Netherlands East Indies Army (KNIL) started to build a 750-mm gauge railways known as Atjeh Tram, which began operating from 1882 to 1942 and later changed its name to Atjeh Staatsspoorwegen (ASS) in 1916.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Its railways assets, now mostly inactive, is under the ownership of the Regional Division I North Sumatra and Aceh of Kereta Api Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Cut Meutia (train) is a train that serves Krueng Geukueh to Krueng Mane in North Aceh Regency.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/aceh] Airports in Aceh include Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport in Aceh Besar Regency (serving Banda Aceh and surrounding areas) and Maimun Saleh Airport in Sabang.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Some kind of limitation on the trade in alcohol can be seen in the Code of Hammurabi (c.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] 1772 BCE) specifically banning the selling of beer for money.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In the early 20th century, much of the impetus for the prohibition movement in the Nordic countries and North America came from moralistic convictions of pietistic Protestants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition movements in the West coincided with the advent of women's suffrage, with newly empowered women as part of the political process strongly supporting policies that curbed alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] After several years, prohibition failed in North America and elsewhere.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Rum-running or bootlegging became widespread, and organized crime took control of the distribution of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Distilleries and breweries in Canada, Mexico and the Caribbean flourished as their products were either consumed by visiting Americans or illegally exported to the United States.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Detroit and Chicago became notorious as havens for prohibition dodgers during the time known as the Roaring Twenties – 75% of all alcohol smuggled into the United States crossed the Detroit–Windsor border.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition generally came to an end in the late 1920s or early 1930s in most of North America and Europe, although a few locations continued prohibition for many more years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In some countries where the dominant religion forbids the use of alcohol, the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages is prohibited or restricted today.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] For example, in Saudi Arabia and Libya alcohol is banned; in Pakistan and Iran it is illegal with exceptions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Generally, prohibition is not completely effective, and tends to drive the market underground instead.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Most countries which have maintained long-standing alcohol bans have predominantly Muslim populations whose religious beliefs forbid them from drinking, but the broad popularity of alcohol has meant prohibition is extremely difficult to enforce in most nations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The vast majority of countries which have at one point fully prohibited alcohol have since reversed it.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Both the United States and Soviet Union implemented total bans on alcohol only to repeal them after less than 15 years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In the British colony of Nigeria, missionary forces demanded prohibition of liquor, which proved highly unpopular.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Both Africans and British found illegal supplies such as secret stills, obtaining colonial liquor permits, and smuggling.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The experiment began in 1890 and was repealed in 1939.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] During the coronavirus outbreak of 2020, alcohol sales, and even the transportation of alcohol outside of one's home, was made illegal.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This order came into effect during the nationwide lockdown on 27 March 2020.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The purpose of the ban was intended to prevent drunken fights, reduce domestic violence, stop drunk driving, and eliminate the weekend binge drinking so prevalent across South Africa.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Police, medics, and analysts estimate—conservatively—that alcohol is involved in, or responsible for, at least 40% of all emergency hospital admissions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] By reducing the number of people within hospitals, and of course within social gatherings, the goal of prohibition was to reduce the rate of transmission, and thus slow the spread of the virus.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] A 2022 study found that the alcohol prohibition reduced injury-induced mortality by at least 14% (a conservative estimate) and sharply reduced violent crime.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Sale of alcohol is illegal in Afghanistan.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In Bangladesh, alcohol is somewhat prohibited due to its proscription in the Islamic faith.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The purchase and consumption is still allowed in the country.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Garo tribe consume a type of rice beer , and Christians in this country drink and purchase wine for their holy communion.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In India alcohol is a state subject and individual states can legislate prohibition, but currently most states do not have prohibition and sale/consumption is freely available in 24 out of 29 states.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition is in force in the states of Mizoram, Gujarat, Bihar and Nagaland, parts of Manipur, and the union territory of Lakshadweep.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] All other states and union territories of India permit the sale of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Election days and certain national holidays such as Independence Day are meant to be "dry days" when liquor sale is not permitted but consumption is allowed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Some Indian states observe dry days on major religious festivals/occasions depending on the popularity of the festival in that region.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Maldives ban the import of alcohol, x-raying all baggage on arrival.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcoholic beverages are available only to foreign tourists on resort islands and may not be taken off the resort.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Pakistan allowed the free sale and consumption of alcohol for three decades from 1947, but restrictions were introduced by Zulfikar Ali Bhutto just weeks before he was removed as prime minister in 1977.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Since then, only members of non-Muslim minorities such as Hindus, Christians and Zoroastrians are allowed to apply for alcohol permits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The monthly quota is dependent upon one's income, but is actually about five bottles of liquor or 100 bottles of beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In a country of 180 million, only about 60 outlets are allowed to sell alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Murree Brewery in Rawalpindi was once the only legal brewery, but today there are more.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The ban officially is enforced by the country's Council of Islamic Ideology, but it is not strictly policed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Members of religious minorities, however, often sell their liquor permits to Muslims as part of a continuing black market trade in alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1955 Sri Lanka passed a law prohibiting adult women from buying alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In January 2018, Finance Minister Mangala Samaraweera announced that the law would be amended, allowing women to legally consume alcohol and work in venues that sell alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The legalization was overruled by President Maithripala Sirisena several days later.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Since the 1979 Islamic Revolution, Muslims are banned from selling and drinking alcohol but some people trade and sell it illegally.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Home production by religious minorities (Zoroastrians, Jews, and Christians) is legal.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The consumption, importation and brewing of, and trafficking in liquor is strictly against the law in Kuwait.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The sale, consumption, importation and brewing of, and trafficking in liquor is strictly against the law in Saudi Arabia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In Brunei, alcohol consumption and sale is banned in public.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol sales in Indonesia are banned in small shops and convenience stores.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] During the Joseon period, laws prohibiting the drinking of alcohol were frequently promulgated when there were major droughts, crop failures, or famines.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The purpose of such bans was to appease the wrath of heaven, and to save food and money (since rice was used to make alcohol).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] A ban was issued almost every year during King Taejong's reign and frequently during the reigns of King Seongjong and King Yeonsangun.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] It was banned again, in 1758 (the 34th year of King Yeongjo).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The bans usually occurred during spring and summer when the droughts were severe.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol is banned only for Muslims in Malaysia due to its Islamic faith and sharia law.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Nevertheless, alcoholic products can easily be found in supermarkets, specialty shops, and convenience stores all over the country.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Non-halal restaurants also typically sell alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] There are only restrictions during elections in the Philippines.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol is prohibited to be sold, furnished, offered, bought, or taken on the day prior to an election and on the day of an election itself.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Hotels and restaurants may secure a prior exemption but even then they are only allowed to serve alcohol to non-Filipino citizens.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Private consumption of alcohol hoarded prior to the ban period is tolerated.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Philippine Commission on Elections may opt to extend the liquor ban.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In the 2013 elections, there was a proposal that it be extended to five days.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This was overturned by the Supreme Court.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Other than election-related prohibition, alcohol is freely sold to anyone above the legal drinking age of 18.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol sales are prohibited during elections from 18:00 the day prior to voting, until the end of the day of voting itself.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol is also prohibited on major Buddhist holy days, and sometimes on royal commemoration days, such as birthdays.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Thailand also enforces time-limited bans on alcohol on a daily basis.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol can only be legally purchased in stores or restaurants between 11:00 and midnight.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The law is enforced by all major retailers (most notably 7-Eleven) and restaurants, but is frequently ignored by the smaller mom-and-pop stores.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Hotels and resorts are exempt from the rules.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The consumption of alcohol is also banned at any time within 200 metres (660 ft) of a filling station (where sale of alcohol is also illegal), schools, temples or hospitals as well as on board any type of road vehicle regardless of whether it is being consumed by the driver or passenger.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] At certain times of the year—Thai New Year (Songkran) is an example—the government may also enforce arbitrary bans on the sale and consumption of alcohol in specific public areas where large scale festivities are due to take place and large crowds are expected.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Thailand strictly regulates alcohol advertising, as specified in the Alcohol Beverage Control Act, B.E.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Sales of alcohol via "electronic channels" (internet) are prohibited.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] On 14 September 2012, the Government of the Czech Republic banned all sales of alcoholic drinks with more than 20% alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] From this date, it was illegal to sell such alcoholic beverages in shops, supermarkets, bars, restaurants, filling stations, e-shops, etc.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This measure was taken in response to the wave of methanol poisoning cases resulting in the deaths of 18 people in the Czech Republic.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Since the beginning of the "methanol affair" the total number of deaths has increased to 25.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The ban was to be valid until further notice, though restrictions were eased towards the end of September.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The last bans on Czech alcohol with regard to the poisoning cases were lifted on 10 October 2012, when neighbouring Slovakia and Poland allowed its import once again.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Nordic countries, with the exception of Denmark, have had a strong temperance movement since the late-1800s, closely linked to the Christian revival movement of the late-19th century, but also to several worker organisations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] As an example, in 1910 the temperance organisations in Sweden had some 330,000 members, which was about 6% of a population of 5.5 million.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This heavily influenced the decisions of Nordic politicians in the early 20th century.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1907, the Faroe Islands passed a law prohibiting all sale of alcohol, which was in force until 1992.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Very restricted private importation from Denmark was allowed from 1928 onwards.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1914, Sweden put in place a rationing system, the Bratt System, in force until 1955.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] A referendum in 1922 rejected an attempt to enforce total prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1915, Iceland instituted total prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The ban for wine was lifted in 1922 and spirits in 1935, but beer remained prohibited until 1989 (circumvented by mixing light beer and spirits).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1916, Norway prohibited distilled beverages, and in 1917 the prohibition was extended to also include fortified wine and beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The wine and beer ban was lifted in 1923, and in 1927 the ban of distilled beverages was also lifted.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1919, Finland enacted prohibition, as one of the first acts after independence from the Russian Empire.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Four previous attempts to institute prohibition in the early twentieth century had failed due to opposition from the tsar.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Today, all Nordic countries except Denmark continue to have strict controls on the sale of alcohol, which is highly taxed (dutied) to the public.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] There are government monopolies in place for selling spirits, wine, and stronger beers in Norway (*Vinmonopolet*), Finland (*Alko*), Sweden (*Systembolaget*), Iceland (*Vínbúðin*), and the Faroe Islands (*Rúsdrekkasøla Landsins*).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Bars and restaurants may, however, import alcoholic beverages directly or through other companies.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Greenland, which is part of the Kingdom of Denmark, does not share its easier controls on the sale of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Greenland has (like Denmark) sales in food shops, but prices are typically high.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Private import when travelling from Denmark is only allowed in small quantities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In the Russian Empire, a limited version of a Dry Law was introduced in 1914.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] It continued through the turmoil of the Russian Revolution of 1917 and the Russian Civil War into the period of Soviet Russia and the Soviet Union until 1925.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The village of Bournville traditionally remains a dry town with no pubs due to the founder John Cadbury's Quaker beliefs and wish for it to remain free of alcohol for the workers at his Cadbury's chocolate factory.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Formed in 1853 and inspired by the Maine law in the United States, the United Kingdom Alliance aimed at promoting a similar law prohibiting the sale of alcohol in the UK.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This hard-line group of prohibitionists was opposed by other temperance organisations who preferred moral persuasion to a legal ban.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This division in the ranks limited the effectiveness of the temperance movement as a whole.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The impotence of legislation in this field was demonstrated when the Sale of Beer Act 1854, which restricted Sunday opening hours, had to be repealed, following widespread rioting.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1859, a prototype prohibition bill was overwhelmingly defeated in the House of Commons.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] At the meeting, Lord Channing said that it was a pity that the whole Cabinet did not follow the example of King George V and Lord Kitchener when in 1914 those two spoke calling for complete prohibition for the duration of the war.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Edwin Scrymgeour served as Member of Parliament for Dundee between 15 November 1922 and 8 October 1931.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] He remains the only person to have ever been elected to the House of Commons on a prohibitionist ticket.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Indigenous peoples in Canada were subject to prohibitory alcohol laws under the Indian Act of 1876.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Sections of the Indian Act regarding liquor were not repealed for over a hundred years, until 1985.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] An official, but non-binding, federal referendum on prohibition was held in 1898.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prime Minister Wilfrid Laurier's government chose not to introduce a federal bill on prohibition, mindful of the strong antipathy in Quebec.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] As a result, Canadian prohibition was instead enacted through laws passed by the provinces during the first 20 years of the 20th century, especially during the 1910s.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Canada did, however, enact a national prohibition from 1918 to 1920 as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Much of the rum-running during prohibition took place in Windsor, Ontario.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The provinces later repealed their prohibition laws, mostly during the 1920s, although some local municipalities remain dry.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Some communities in the southern Mexican state of Chiapas are under the control of the libertarian socialist Zapatista Army of National Liberation, and often ban alcohol as part of what was described as "a collective decision".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This prohibition has been used by many villages as a way to decrease domestic violence and has generally been favored by women.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This prohibition, however, is not recognized by federal Mexican law as the Zapatista movement is strongly opposed by the federal government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The sale and purchase of alcohol is prohibited on and the night before certain national holidays (*Fiestas Patrias*), such as the birthdate of Benito Juárez and *Día de la Revolución*, which are meant to be dry nationally.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The same "dry law" applies to the days before presidential elections every six years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition in the United States focused on the manufacture, transportation, and sale of alcoholic beverages; exceptions were made for medicinal and religious uses.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Alcohol consumption was never illegal under federal law.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Nationwide Prohibition did not begin in the United States until January 1920, when the Eighteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Eighteenth amendment was ratified in 1919, and was repealed in December 1933 with the ratification of the Twenty-first Amendment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Concern over excessive alcohol consumption began during the American colonial era, when fines were imposed for drunken behavior and for selling liquor without a license.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In the mid-19th century evangelical Protestants denounced drinking as sinful and demanded the prohibition of the sale of beer, wine and liquor.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Apart from Maine, they had limited success until the early 20th century.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] By the 1840s the temperance movement was actively encouraging individuals to immediately stop drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] However, the issue of slavery, and then the Civil War, overshadowed the temperance movement until the 1870s.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition was a major reform movement from the 1870s until the 1920s, when nationwide prohibition went into effect.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] It was supported by evangelical Protestant churches, especially the Methodists, Baptists, Presbyterians, Disciples of Christ, Congregationalists, Quakers, and Scandinavian Lutherans.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Opposition came from Catholics, Episcopalians, and German Lutherans.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Women's Crusade of 1873 and the Woman's Christian Temperance Union (WCTU), founded in 1874, were means through which certain women organized and demanded political action, well before they were granted the vote.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The WCTU and the Prohibition Party were major players until the 20th century, when the Anti-Saloon League emerged as the movement's leader.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] By 1913, 9 states had statewide prohibition and 31 others had local option laws in effect.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The League then turned their efforts toward attaining a constitutional amendment and grassroots support for nationwide prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The German American community was the base of the beer industry and became a pariah when the U.S. declared war on Germany in 1917.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] A new constitutional amendment passed Congress in December 1917 and was ratified by the states in 1919.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] It prohibited "the manufacture, sale, or transportation of intoxicating liquors within, the importation thereof into, or the exportation thereof." On October 28, 1919, Congress passed the National Prohibition Act, known as the Volstead Act, to implement the new 18th Amendment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] After a year's required delay, national prohibition began on January 16, 1920.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Initially, alcohol consumption nosedived to about 30% of its pre-Prohibition levels, but within a few years, the illicit market grew to roughly two-thirds.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Illegal stills flourished in remote rural areas as well as city slums, and large quantities were smuggled from Canada.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Bootlegging became a major business activity for organized crime groups, under leaders such as Al Capone in Chicago and Lucky Luciano in New York City.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition lost support during the Great Depression, from 1929.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The repeal movement was initiated and financed by the Association Against the Prohibition Amendment, and Pauline Sabin, a wealthy Republican, founded the Women's Organization for National Prohibition Reform (WONPR).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Repeal of Prohibition in the United States was accomplished with the ratification of the Twenty-first Amendment on December 5, 1933.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Between 1832 and 1953, federal legislation prohibited the sale of alcohol to Native Americans, with very limited success.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] After 1953, Native American communities and reservations were permitted to pass their own local ordinances governing the sale of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In the 21st century, there are still counties and parishes within the United States known as "dry", where the sale of alcohol is prohibited or restricted.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The same is done during Holy Week as a measure to reduce the alarming rate of road traffic accidents during these holidays.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Australian Capital Territory (then the Federal Capital Territory) was the first jurisdiction in Australia to have prohibition laws.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In 1911, King O'Malley, then Minister of Home Affairs, shepherded laws through Parliament preventing new issue or transfer of licences to sell alcohol, to address unruly behaviour among workers building the new capital city.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition was partial, since possession of alcohol purchased outside of the Territory remained legal and the few pubs that had existing licences could continue to operate.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Federal Parliament repealed the laws after residents of the Federal Capital Territory voted for the end of them in a 1928 plebiscite.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Since then, some state governments and local councils have enacted dry areas.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] This is where the purchase or consumption of alcohol is only permitted in licensed areas such as liquor stores, clubs, cafes, bars, hotels, restaurants, and also private homes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In public places such as streets, parks, and squares, consumption is not permitted, but carrying bottles that were purchased at licensed venues is allowed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Almost all dry areas are small defined districts within larger urban or rural communities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] More recently, alcohol has been prohibited in many remote Indigenous communities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Penalties for transporting alcohol into these "dry" communities are severe and can result in confiscation of any vehicles involved; in dry areas within the Northern Territory, all vehicles used to transport alcohol are seized.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In New Zealand, prohibition was a moralistic reform movement begun in the mid-1880s by the Protestant evangelical and Nonconformist churches and the Woman's Christian Temperance Union and after 1890 by the Prohibition League.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] It assumed that individual virtue was all that was needed to carry the colony forward from a pioneering society to a more mature one, but it never achieved its goal of national prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Both the Church of England and the largely Irish Catholic Church rejected prohibition as an intrusion of government into the church's domain, while the growing labor movement saw capitalism rather than alcohol as the enemy.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Reformers hinged their aspiration on the women's vote, in which New Zealand was a pioneer, would swing the balance, but the women were not as well organized as in other countries.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition had a majority in a national referendum in 1911, but needed a 60% vote to pass.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The movement kept trying in the 1920s, losing three more referendums by close votes; it managed to keep in place a 6 pm closing hour for pubs and Sunday closing.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The Depression and war years effectively ended the movement, but their 6 pm closing hour remained until October 1967 when it was extended to 10 pm.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] For many years, referendums were held for individual towns or electorates, often coincident with general elections.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The ballots determined whether these individual areas would be "dry" – that is, alcohol could not be purchased or consumed in public in these areas.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] One notable example was the southern city of Invercargill, which was dry from 1907 to 1943.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] People wanting alcohol usually travelled to places outside the city (such as the nearby township of Lorneville or the town of Winton) to drink in the local pubs or purchase alcohol to take back home.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The last bastion of this 'dry' area remains in force in the form of a licensing trust that still to this day governs the sale of liquor in Invercargill.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The city does not allow the sale of alcohol (beer and wine included) in supermarkets unlike in the majority of New Zealand, and all form of alcohol regardless of the sort can only be sold in bars and liquor stores.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Prohibition was of limited success in New Zealand as—like in other countries—it led to organised bootlegging.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] The most famous bootlegged alcohol in New Zealand was that produced in the Hokonui Hills close to the town of Gore (not coincidentally, the nearest large town to Invercargill).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] Even today, the term "Hokonui" conjures up images of illicit whisky to many New Zealanders.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In many countries in Latin America, the Philippines, Thailand, Turkey, India, and several US states, the sale but not the consumption of alcohol is prohibited before and during elections.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-ban] In Spanish-speaking countries, this is called a *Ley Seca* ('dry law').
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-beverage] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Although the minimum legal age to *purchase* alcohol is 21 in all U.S. states and most territories , the legal details for *consumption* vary greatly.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Although some states prohibit alcohol usage for people under 18, the majority have exceptions that permit consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Underage drinking has become an activity primarily done in secrecy.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] In what is known as pre-gaming or pre-partying, underage drinkers may hide their alcohol consumption by drinking quickly before they go out.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Brittany Levine explained in her article "Pre-Gaming" in USA Today that "of all drinking events involving pre-partying, 80% involved additional drinking afterward," and that pre-partying is involved in approximately 45% of all drinking events.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Most states decided on 21 as the drinking age after Prohibition, but the 26th Amendment allowed individuals 18 and older to vote and serve in the military, so several states lowered the drinking age as well.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] However, President Ronald Reagan, influenced by groups such as Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD) and Remove Intoxicated Drivers (RID), decided to federally establish a 21+ drinking age by signing the National Minimum Drinking Age Act of 1984.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] He believed that doing so would decrease the number of crashes related to drunk driving, because, he claimed, states with a drinking age of 21+ did not have as many drunk driving crashes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Reagan said that although he wished states would create their own legislation to increase the drinking age, a federal law had to be implemented to avoid blood borders, or teenagers driving to the nearest state with a lower drinking age.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Reagan threatened states with withholding 5% of federal funding for highways if they did not comply with increasing the drinking age to 21.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] In 2007, the drinking age debate in the United States was renewed when nonprofit organization Choose Responsibility began promoting the lowering of the drinking age coupled with education and rules to persuade people to drink responsibly before they are of legal age.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Before one is eligible to buy, possess and consume alcohol, an alcohol education class must be completed in its entirety and each teen must pass a final examination before licensing can occur.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] If a teen has any alcohol-related law violations before they turn 18, including a zero-tolerance DUI triggered by a BAC of 0.01% or higher, they will face a minimum one-year delay per violation before becoming eligible to be licensed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] In 2008, McCardell and the presidents of over 100 U.S. colleges and universities launched the Amethyst Initiative, a campaign to debate the effectiveness of present alcohol laws.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] In 2008, Gallup reported that 77% of the population over 18 oppose the 18-year drinking age.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] As it stands, any state that lowers its alcohol purchase or possession age would lose five percent of its federal highway funding.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] This could range from a $6 million–150 million loss for any single state.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] The Brief Alcohol Screening and Intervention for College Students (BASICS) program consists of a brief survey given to students to help them assess their alcohol usage against other students.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] It also consists of one or two counseling sessions granted to the students to provide support and not be confrontational regarding their alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] The Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration created the "Talk.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] They Hear You" campaign in 2013 that involved a mobile app, and to assist parents with having conversations about alcohol usage to their children, the "Talk.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] To summarize the motivations for underage drinking, cultural norms allow underage drinking while social pressures facilitate them.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Although the legal drinking age is set at 21, drinking at age 18 or upon entrance into college is the culturally accepted limit.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] This cultural permission is the primary reason many college students ignore laws concerning drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] In addition to cultural motivations, students are socially expected to drink.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Many social gatherings are centered on drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Furthermore, besides feeling the need to drink in order to be accepted, alcohol intoxication provides students who may be shy or feel out of their element with enough liquid courage to enjoy themselves.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Another major factor is for adolescents who grew up in households where drinking was common, encouraged, or provided to them.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] One study from 2005 showed that 26% of adults think underage drinking is okay if an adult is present.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Those that are for lowering the drinking age generally argue that the moderate consumption of alcohol frequently as a complement to a meal or drink with friends is preferable to and healthier than the binge drinking habits more often associated with dry countries such as the United States.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] These opinions generally lead to the argument that it is far more effective and beneficial for laws to monitor, limit, and guide healthy drinking habits rather than to outright ban it.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Furthermore, it is argued that alcohol misuse occurs—at least in part—as a result of the stringent drinking laws.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] It is said that if a drinking age weren't strictly enforced and people below the age of 18 had opportunities to learn how to drink responsibility before college, fewer teenagers would misuse alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Heath, a Professor at Brown points out the ‘forbidden fruit’ syndrome that is created when the drinking age is so high.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] In contrast to countries with low drinking ages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Those who argue for maintaining and even strengthening current drinking laws, however, citing past examples, generally argue that injuries and deaths related to drinking are bad enough presently.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] They also argue that initiatives to implement gradual drinking laws or educational programs are optimistic and unrealistic.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Furthermore, they propose that drinking and driving related problems are rampant enough among those who are not legally of age and that lowering the drinking age would only enable these habits further, causing an even higher volume of alcohol-related problems.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Although the incidence of underage drinking is still significant, government, university and national statistics have confirmed that alcohol use and binge drinking among high school students has declined steadily over the past three decades, and continues to decline annually.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] According to a United States Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration study involving 30,000 youths 12 to 20 years of age, between 2002 and 2013 the percentage of underage drinkers declined from 28.8% to 22.7%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Underage binge drinkers decreased 19.3% to 14.2%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] A study conducted in December 2014 by the University of Michigan also found that 75% of senior high school students disapproved of drinking excessively on the weekends.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Alcohol still proved to be the favored substance among American youths however, with tobacco and illicit drugs following in rank.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] According to data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, obtained by The Hill, drug and alcohol-related deaths among children aged 15 to 19 have increased from 788 in 2018 to 1,755 in 2021.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Those who oppose a complete ban on underage drinking argue that it is important that minors be introduced to alcohol in a controlled environment, so that supervision and guidance might occur instead of experimentation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Some parents are willing to provide alcohol for their children if they drink it in a controlled environment.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Furnishing alcohol to one's own children is permitted in 31 states, while it's illegal to do so for other people's children in all fifty states.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Social host ordinances have been enacted in a number of jurisdictions to attempt to limit the parties where adults may permit minors to drink.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Social host laws or ordinances have proliferated in the last ten years because it has been too difficult for law enforcement to prove which adults furnished or served alcohol to minors in their own home, so it permits them to cite or arrest the adult who has control of the premises.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Due to the difficulty in proving these cases, some states make this an affirmative defense that the defendant must prove consumption was legally permissible.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] According to the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism's 2024 report, most Americans report ever drinking: 79.2% of those 12+, including 85.0% of adults 18+ and 21.3% of teens 12–17.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Men consistently report slightly higher prevalence than women across lifetime, past-year, and past-month measures.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Patterns vary by race/ethnicity: among people 12+, White respondents generally show higher prevalence, while Asian respondents show lower prevalence.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] Taken together, the 2024 snapshot shows alcohol use remains common, especially among adults, with notable demographic differences and substantially lower (but non-trivial) prevalence among adolescents.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] According to the 2025 *Monitoring the Future* survey, underage drinking continued a long-term decline among U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-consumption-by-youth-in-the-united-states] 8th, 10th, and 12th graders, with lifetime, past-year, and past-30-day alcohol use at or near historic low levels; binge drinking rates among teens also remained low in 2025.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Short-term adverse effects include generalized impairment of neurocognitive function, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, and symptoms of hangover.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is addictive and can result in alcohol use disorder, dependence, and withdrawal upon cessation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The adverse effects of alcohol on health are most significant when it is used in excessive quantities or with heavy frequency.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, in 2023, the World Health Organization published a statement in The Lancet Public Health that concluded, "no safe amount of alcohol consumption for cancers and health can be established".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In high amounts, alcohol may cause loss of consciousness or, in severe cases, death.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Many governmental agencies and organizations issue alcohol consumption recommendations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has been produced and consumed by humans for its psychoactive effects since at least 13,000 years ago, when the earliest known beer was brewed by the Natufian culture in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is the second most consumed psychoactive drug globally, behind caffeine, with global sales of alcoholic beverages exceeding US$1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol is generally socially acceptable and is legal in most countries, unlike with many other recreational substances.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, there are often restrictions on alcohol sale and use, for instance a minimum age for drinking and laws against public drinking and drinking and driving.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has considerable societal and cultural significance and has important social roles in much of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drinking establishments, such as bars and nightclubs, revolve primarily around the sale and consumption of alcoholic beverages, and parties, festivals, and social gatherings commonly involve alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is related to various societal problems, including drunk driving, accidental injuries, sexual assaults, domestic abuse, and violent crime.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol remains illegal for sale and consumption in a number of countries, mainly in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] While some religions, including Islam, prohibit alcohol consumption, other religions, such as Christianity and Shinto, utilize alcohol in sacrament and libation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is commonly consumed as the recreational active substance of alcoholic beverages such as beer, wine, and spirits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Consumption in social settings may enhance sociability.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] While research on the societal benefits of alcohol is rare, in a study from the UK, regular but moderate drinking was correlated with happiness, feeling that life was worthwhile, and satisfaction with life.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Community pubs had less variation in visible group sizes and longer, more focused conversations than those in city centre bars.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drinking regularly at a community pub led to higher trust in others and better networking with the local community, compared to non-drinkers and city centre bar drinkers.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, according to a causal path analysis, alcohol consumption was not the cause, but rather satisfaction with life resulted in greater happiness and an inclination to visit pubs and develop a regular drinking venue.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) uses a figure of 6.93 kilocalories (29.0 kJ) per gram of alcohol (5.47 kcal or 22.9 kJ per mL) for calculating food energy.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] For distilled spirits, a standard serving in the United States is 44 mL (1.5 US fl oz), which at 40% ethanol (80 proof), would be 14 grams and 98 calories.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic drinks are considered empty calorie foods because other than food energy they contribute no essential nutrients.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, alcohol is a significant source of food energy for individuals with alcoholism and those who engage in binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] For example, individuals with drunkorexia engage in the combination of self-imposed malnutrition and binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In alcoholics who get most of their daily calories from alcohol, a deficiency of thiamine (vitamin B1) can produce Korsakoff syndrome, which is associated with serious brain damage.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] When fomepizole is not available, ethanol can be used to treat or prevent methanol or ethylene glycol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The rate-limiting steps for the elimination of ethanol are in common with these substances, so it competes with other alcohols for the alcohol dehydrogenase enzyme.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Methanol itself is not highly toxic, but its metabolites formaldehyde and formic acid are; therefore, to reduce the rate of production and concentration of these harmful metabolites, ethanol can be ingested or injected.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] This avoids the production of toxic aldehyde and carboxylic acid derivatives, and reduces the more serious toxic effects of the glycols when crystallized in the kidneys.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethylene glycol poisoning can be treated in the same way.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a long association of military use, and has been called "liquid courage" for its role in preparing troops for battle, anesthetize injured soldiers, and celebrate military victories.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It has also served as a coping mechanism for combat stress reactions and a means of decompression from combat to everyday life.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can have analgesic (pain-relieving) effects, which is why some people with chronic pain turn to alcohol to self-medicate and try to alleviate their physical discomfort.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] People with social anxiety disorder commonly self-medicate with alcohol to overcome their highly set inhibitions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, self-medicating excessively for prolonged periods of time with alcohol often makes the symptoms of anxiety or depression worse.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] This is believed to occur as a result of the changes in brain chemistry from long-term use.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A 2023 systematic review highlights the non-addictive use of alcohol for managing developmental issues, personality traits, and psychiatric symptoms, emphasizing the need for informed, harm-controlled approaches to alcohol consumption within a personalized health policy framework.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is classified as a teratogen—a substance known to cause birth defects; according to the U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), alcohol consumption by women who are not using birth control increases the risk of fetal alcohol spectrum disorders (FASDs).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] This group of conditions encompasses fetal alcohol syndrome, partial fetal alcohol syndrome, alcohol-related neurodevelopmental disorder, static encephalopathy, and alcohol-related birth defects.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The CDC currently recommends complete abstinence from alcoholic beverages for women of child-bearing age who are pregnant or trying to become pregnant.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In patients who have a peptic ulcer disease (PUD), the mucosal layer is broken down by ethanol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] PUD is commonly associated with the bacteria *Helicobacter pylori*, which secretes a toxin that weakens the mucosal wall, allowing acid and protein enzymes to penetrate the weakened barrier.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Because alcohol stimulates the stomach to secrete acid, a person with PUD should avoid drinking alcohol on an empty stomach.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol causes more acid release, which further damages the already-weakened stomach wall.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Complications of this disease could include a burning pain in the abdomen, bloating, and, in severe cases, the presence of dark black stools indicate internal bleeding.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A person who drinks alcohol regularly is strongly advised to reduce their intake to prevent PUD aggravation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol-containing beverages can cause alcohol flush reactions, exacerbations of rhinitis, and, more seriously and commonly, bronchoconstriction in patients with a history of asthma, and in some cases, urticarial skin eruptions, and systemic dermatitis.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption can cause hypoglycemia in diabetics on certain medications, such as insulin or sulfonylurea, by blocking gluconeogenesis.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol increases insulin response to glucose promoting fat storage and hindering carbohydrate and fat oxidation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] This excess processing in the liver acetyl CoA can lead to fatty liver disease and eventually alcoholic liver disease.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] This progression can lead to further complications, alcohol-related liver disease may cause exocrine pancreatic insufficiency, the inability to properly digest food due to a lack or reduction of digestive enzymes made by the pancreas.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of short-term and long-term adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has both short-term, and long-term effects on the memory, and sleep.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It also has reinforcement-related adverse effects, including alcoholism, dependence, and withdrawal.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is directly related to considerable morbidity and mortality, for instance due to intoxication and alcohol-related health problems.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The World Health Organization advises that there is no safe level of alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Many of the toxic and unpleasant actions of alcohol in the body are mediated by its carcinogenic byproduct acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The amount of ethanol in the body is typically quantified by blood alcohol content (BAC); weight of ethanol per unit volume of blood.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Small doses of ethanol, in general, are stimulant-like and produce euphoria and relaxation; people experiencing these symptoms tend to become talkative and less inhibited, and may exhibit poor judgement.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] At higher dosages (BAC > 1 gram/liter), ethanol acts as a central nervous system (CNS) depressant, producing at progressively higher dosages, impaired sensory and motor function, slowed cognition, stupefaction, unconsciousness, and possible death.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A hangover is the experience of various unpleasant physiological and psychological effects usually following the consumption of alcohol, such as wine, beer, and liquor.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Hangovers can last for several hours or for more than 24 hours.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The long-term effects of alcohol have been extensively researched.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The health effects of long-term alcohol consumption vary depending on the amount consumed.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Even light drinking poses health risks, but atypically small amounts of alcohol may have health benefits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism causes severe health consequences which outweigh any potential benefits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Long-term alcohol consumption is capable of damaging nearly every organ and system in the body.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In addition, damage to the central nervous system and peripheral nervous system (e.g., painful peripheral neuropathy) can occur from chronic heavy alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] There is also an increased risk for accidental injuries, for example, those sustained in traffic accidents and falls.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Excessive alcohol consumption can have a negative impact on aging.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Conversely, light intake of alcohol may have some beneficial effects.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The association of alcohol intake with reduced cardiovascular risk has been noted since 1904 and remains even after adjusting for known confounders.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Light alcohol intake is also associated with reduced risk of type 2 diabetes, gastritis, and cholelithiasis.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, these are only observational studies and high-quality evidence for the beneficial effects of alcohol is nonexistent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol causes a plethora of detrimental effects in society.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in delphic analysis regarding 20 popular recreational substances.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was ranked 6th in dependence, 11th in physical harm, and 2nd in social harm.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is stereotypically associated with crime, more so than other drugs like marijuana.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Many emergency room visits involve alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] As many as 15% of employees show problematic alcohol-related behaviors in the workplace, such as drinking before going to work or even drinking on the job.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drunk dialing refers to an intoxicated person making phone calls that they would not likely make if sober.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol availability and consumption rates and alcohol rates are positively associated with nuisance, loitering, panhandling, and disorderly conduct in open spaces.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking, or heavy episodic drinking, is drinking alcoholic beverages with an intention of becoming intoxicated by heavy consumption of alcohol over a short period of time.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking is associated with risks such as suicide, sexual assault, cardiovascular issues, and brain damage, more acutely than alcohol use in general.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism or its medical diagnosis *alcohol use disorder* refers to alcohol addiction, alcohol dependence, dipsomania, and/or alcohol abuse.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It is a major problem and many health problems as well as death can result from excessive alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is linked to a lifespan that is reduced by about 12 years relative to the average person.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In 2004, it was estimated that 4% of deaths worldwide were attributable to alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Deaths from alcohol are split about evenly between acute causes (e.g., overdose, accidents) and chronic conditions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The leading chronic alcohol-related condition associated with death is alcoholic liver disease.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is also associated with cognitive impairment and organic brain damage.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Some researchers have found that even one alcoholic drink a day increases an individual's risk of health problems by 0.4%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Two or more consecutive alcohol-free days a week have been recommended to improve health and break dependence.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Discontinuation of alcohol after extended heavy use and associated tolerance development (resulting in dependence) can result in alcohol withdrawal.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the most dangerous drugs to withdraw from.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol withdrawal can cause confusion, paranoia, anxiety, insomnia, agitation, tremors, fever, nausea, vomiting, autonomic dysfunction, seizures, and hallucinations.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Delirium tremens is a condition that develops in some cases of severe withdrawal, with onset typically 48–72 hours after discontinuation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It is considered a medical emergency and should be treated in an inpatient or intensive care unit.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Symptoms of ethanol overdose may include nausea, vomiting, CNS depression, coma, acute respiratory failure, or death.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Levels of even less than 0.1% can cause intoxication, with unconsciousness often occurring at 0.3–0.4%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Death from ethanol consumption is possible when blood alcohol levels reach 0.4%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A blood level of 0.5% or more is commonly fatal.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The oral median lethal dose (LD50) of ethanol in rats is 5,628 mg/kg.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Directly translated to human beings, this would mean that if a person who weighs 70 kg (150 lb) drank a 500 mL (17 US fl oz) glass of pure ethanol, they would have an estimated 50% risk of dying.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The highest blood alcohol level ever recorded, in which the subject survived, is 1.41%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol-induced dose dumping (AIDD) is an unintended rapid release of large amounts of a given drug, when administered through a modified-release dosage while co-ingesting ethanol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] This is considered a pharmaceutical disadvantage due to the high risk of causing drug-induced toxicity by increasing the absorption and serum concentration above the therapeutic window of the drug.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The best way to prevent this interaction is by avoiding the co-ingestion of both substances or using specific controlled-release formulations that are resistant to AIDD.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Particular drugs of concern are antipsychotics and certain antidepressants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can intensify the sedation caused by hypnotics and sedatives such as barbiturates, benzodiazepines, sedative antihistamines, opioids, nonbenzodiazepines/Z-drugs (such as zolpidem and zopiclone).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Disulfiram inhibits the enzyme acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, which in turn results in buildup of acetaldehyde, a toxic metabolite of ethanol with unpleasant effects.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The medication or drug is commonly used to treat alcohol use disorder, and results in immediate hangover-like symptoms upon consumption of alcohol, this effect is widely known as disulfiram effect.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is an antibacterial agent that kills bacteria by damaging cellular DNA and hence cellular function.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is usually given to people who have diarrhea caused by *Clostridioides difficile* bacteria.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Patients who are taking metronidazole are sometimes advised to avoid alcohol, even after 1 hour following the last dose.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Although older data suggested a possible disulfiram-like effect of metronidazole, newer data has challenged this and suggests it does not actually have this effect.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and alcohol both increase gastrointestinal events such as gastrointestinal bleeding and peptic ulcers.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Taking the two together further increases the risk additively.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The risk of stomach bleeding is still increased when aspirin is taken with alcohol or warfarin.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol enhances the bioavailability of methylphenidate (elevated plasma dexmethylphenidate).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethylphenidate formation appears to be more common when large quantities of methylphenidate and alcohol are consumed at the same time, such as in non-medical use or overdose scenarios.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, only a small percent of the consumed methylphenidate is converted to ethylphenidate.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] While nicotinis mimic the name of classic cocktails like the appletini (their name deriving from "martini"), combining nicotine with alcohol may cause adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Tobacco and nicotine actually heighten cravings for alcohol, making this a risky mix.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Controlled animal and human studies showed that caffeine (energy drinks) in combination with alcohol increased the craving for more alcohol more strongly than alcohol alone.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] These findings correspond to epidemiological data that people who consume energy drinks generally showed an increased tendency to take alcohol and other substances.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol interacts with cocaine *in vivo* to produce cocaethylene, another psychoactive substance which may be substantially more cardiotoxic than either cocaine or alcohol by themselves.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In combination with cannabis, ethanol increases plasma tetrahydrocannabinol levels, which suggests that ethanol may increase the absorption of tetrahydrocannabinol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Excessive use of alcohol is known to affect the metabolism of warfarin and can elevate the INR, and thus increase the risk of bleeding.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) product insert on warfarin states that alcohol should be avoided.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Cleveland Clinic suggests that when taking warfarin one should not drink more than "one beer, 6 oz of wine, or one shot of alcohol per day".
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Use of isoniazid should be carefully monitored in daily alcohol drinkers since they may be more likely to develop isoniazid-associated hepatitis.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol works in the brain primarily by increasing the effects of GABA (γ-aminobutyric acid), the major inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain; by facilitating GABA's actions in the GABAA receptor, alcohol suppresses the activity of the central nervous system.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol also directly affects a number of other neurotransmitter systems including those of glutamate, glycine, acetylcholine, and serotonin.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The pleasurable effects of alcohol ingestion are the result of increased levels of dopamine and endogenous opioids in the reward pathways of the brain.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] After oral ingestion, ethanol is absorbed via the stomach and intestines into the bloodstream.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is highly water-soluble and diffuses passively throughout the entire body, including the brain.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Soon after ingestion, it begins to be metabolized, 90% or more by the liver.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] One standard drink is sufficient to almost completely saturate the liver's capacity to metabolize alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The main metabolite is acetaldehyde, a toxic carcinogen.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Acetaldehyde is then further metabolized into ionic acetate by the enzyme aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Acetate is not carcinogenic and has low toxicity, but has been implicated in causing hangovers.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Acetate is further broken down into carbon dioxide and water and eventually eliminated from the body through urine and breath.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] 5 to 10% of ethanol is excreted unchanged in the breath, urine, and sweat.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is also known chemically as alcohol, ethyl alcohol, or drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It is a simple alcohol with a molecular formula of C2H6O and a molecular weight of 46.0684 g/mol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The molecular formula of ethanol may also be written as CH3−CH2−OH or as C2H5−OH.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The latter can also be thought of as an ethyl group linked to a hydroxyl (alcohol) group and can be abbreviated as EtOH.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is a volatile, flammable, colorless liquid with a slight characteristic odor.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Aside from its use as a psychoactive and recreational substance, ethanol is also commonly used as an antiseptic and disinfectant, a chemical and medicinal solvent, and a fuel.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is only one of several types of chemical alcohols, and has a variety of analogues.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Most other alcohols are considered poisonous.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In general, higher alcohols are less toxic.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages are sometimes laced with toxic alcohols.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The toxicity of isopropyl alcohol is about twice that of ethanol; a mild, brief exposure to isopropyl alcohol is unlikely to cause any serious harm, although ingesting significant quantities can lead to vomiting, abdominal pain, and internal bleeding.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ingestion of as little as 3.16 grams of methanol can cause irreversible optic nerve damage, and the oral LD50 for humans is estimated to be 56.2 grams.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Many methanol poisoning incidents have occurred through history. n-Butanol is reported to produce similar effects to those of ethanol and relatively low toxicity (one-sixth of that of ethanol in one rat study).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] However, its vapors can produce eye irritation, and inhalation can cause pulmonary edema.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Acetone (propanone) is a ketone rather than an alcohol, and is reported to produce similar toxic effects; it can be extremely damaging to the cornea.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Although ethanol is the most prevalent alcohol in alcoholic beverages, alcoholic beverages contain several types of psychoactive alcohols, that are categorized as primary, secondary, or tertiary.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Primary and secondary alcohols, are oxidized to aldehydes, and ketones, respectively, while tertiary alcohols are generally resistant to oxidation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Lucas test differentiates between primary, secondary, and tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The tertiary alcohol *tert*-amyl alcohol (TAA), also known as 2-methylbutan-2-ol (2M2B), has a history of use as a hypnotic and anesthetic, as do other tertiary alcohols such as methylpentynol, ethchlorvynol, and chloralodol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Unlike primary alcohols like ethanol, these tertiary alcohols cannot be oxidized into aldehyde or carboxylic acid metabolites, which are often toxic, and for this reason, these compounds are safer in comparison.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Other relatives of ethanol with similar effects include chloral hydrate, paraldehyde, and many volatile and inhalational anesthetics (e.g., chloroform, diethyl ether, and isoflurane).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is produced naturally as a byproduct of the metabolic processes of yeast and hence is present in any yeast habitat, including even endogenously in humans, but it does not cause raised blood alcohol content as seen in the rare medical condition auto-brewery syndrome (ABS).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It is manufactured through hydration of ethylene or by brewing via fermentation of sugars with yeast (most commonly *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The sugars are commonly obtained from sources like steeped cereal grains (e.g., barley), grape juice, and sugarcane products (e.g., molasses, sugarcane juice).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol–water mixture which can be further purified via distillation.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the oldest recreational drugs.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The word "Alcohol" originates from the Arabic word *al-kuhul,* which refers to a fine metallic powder that was used to paint the eyelids darker.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages have been produced since the Neolithic period, as early as 7000 BC in China.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was brewed as early as 7,000 to 6,650 BCE in northern China.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Gin Craze was a period in the first half of the 18th century when the consumption of gin increased rapidly in Great Britain, especially in London.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] By 1743, The average English person was drinking 2.2 gallons (10 litres) of gin per year.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Sale of Spirits Act 1750 (commonly known as the Gin Act 1751) was an Act of the Parliament of Great Britain (24 Geo.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] 40) which was enacted to reduce the consumption of gin and other distilled spirits, a popular pastime that was regarded as one of the primary causes of crime in London.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The rum ration (also called the tot) was a daily amount of rum given to sailors on Royal Navy ships.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] It started 1866 and was abolished in 1970 after concerns that the intake of strong alcohol would lead to unsteady hands when working machinery.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Andrew Johnson alcoholism debate is the dispute, originally conducted among the general public, and now typically a question for historians, about whether or not Andrew Johnson, the 17th president of the United States (1865–1869), drank to excess.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The prohibition in the United States era was the period from 1920 to 1933 when the United States prohibited the production, importation, transportation, and sale of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The nationwide ban on alcoholic beverages, was repealed by the passage of the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution on December 5, 1933.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Bratt System was a system that was used in Sweden (1919–1955) and similarly in Finland (1944–1970) to control alcohol consumption, by rationing of liquor.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Every citizen allowed to consume alcohol was given a booklet called a motbok (viinakortti in Finland), in which a stamp was added each time a purchase was made at Systembolaget (in Sweden) and Alko (in Finland).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A similar system also existed in Estonia between July 1, 1920, to December 31, 1925.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The stamps were based on the amount of alcohol bought.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] When a certain amount of alcohol had been bought, the owner of the booklet had to wait until next month to buy more.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The Medicinal Liquor Prescriptions Act of 1933 was a law passed by Congress in response to the abuse of medicinal liquor prescriptions during Prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Gilbert Paul Jordan (aka The Boozing Barber) was a Canadian serial killer who is believed to have committed the so-called "alcohol murders" between 1965–c.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The consumption of alcohol is deeply embedded in social practices and rituals, often celebrated as a cornerstone of community gatherings and personal milestones.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drinking culture is the set of traditions and social behaviours that surround the consumption of alcoholic beverages as a recreational drug and social lubricant.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption is fully legal and available in most countries of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Home made alcoholic beverages with low alcohol content like wine, and beer is also legal in most countries, but distilling moonshine outside of a registered distillery remains illegal in most of them.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Some majority-Muslim countries, such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Pakistan, Iran, and Libya prohibit the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages because they are forbidden by Islam.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Also, laws banning alcohol consumption are found in some Indian states as well as some Native American reservations in the U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In addition, there are regulations on alcohol sales and use in many countries throughout the world.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] For instance, the majority of countries have a minimum legal drinking age to purchase or consume alcoholic beverages, although there are often exceptions such as underage consumption of small amounts of alcohol with parental supervision.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Also, some countries have bans on public intoxication.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Drinking while driving or intoxicated driving is frequently outlawed, and it may be illegal to have an open container of alcohol or liquor bottle in an automobile, bus, or aircraft.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The legality of sex under alcohol influence varies by country and the threshold of "too drunk" for sexual consent can be ambiguous.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Religion and alcohol have a complex history.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The world's religions have had different relationships with alcohol, reflecting diverse cultural, social, and religious practices across different traditions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] While some religions strictly prohibit alcohol consumption, viewing it as sinful or harmful to spiritual and physical well-being, others incorporate it into their rituals and ceremonies.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Throughout history, alcohol has held significant roles in religious observances, from the use of sacramental wine in Christian sacraments to the offering and moderate drinking of omiki (sacramental sake) in Shinto purification rituals.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A study in 2015 found that alcohol and tobacco use combined resulted in a significant health burden, costing over a quarter of a billion disability-adjusted life years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Illicit drug use caused tens of millions more disability-adjusted life years.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] According to *The Lancet*, 'four industries (tobacco, unhealthy food, fossil fuel, and alcohol) are responsible for at least a third of global deaths per year'.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] In 2024, the World Health Organization published a report including these figures.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Many Native Americans in the United States have been harmed by, or become addicted to, drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] Qualitative analysis reveals that the alcohol industry likely misinforms the public about the dangers of alcohol, similar to the tobacco industry.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The alcohol industry influences alcohol policy and health messages, including those for schoolchildren.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The alcohol consumption recommendations (or *safe limits*) varies from no intake, to daily, weekly, or daily/weekly guidelines provided by health agencies of governments.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] A standard drink is a measure of alcohol consumption representing a fixed amount of pure ethanol, used in relation to recommendations about alcohol consumption and its relative risks to health.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-drug] The size of a standard drink varies from 8g to 20g across countries, but 10g alcohol (12.7 millilitres) is used in the World Health Organization (WHO) Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT)'s questionnaire form example, and has been adopted by more countries than any other amount.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Currently, there are no alcohol bans being enforced in Indonesia, with the exception of Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since 2014, anyone found consuming alcohol or breaching the codes on moral conduct, whether residents or visitors to Aceh, could face between six and nine cane lashes.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In other parts of Indonesia, to appease the Islamic parties and pressure groups, the government agreed to apply mild restriction measures on alcohol, which includes high taxation and limited bans.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia is among the countries that apply high taxes on imported alcoholic beverages; in 2015, import tax on alcohol jumped to 150%.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in 2015, the Indonesian government banned the sale of alcohol from minimarkets and small shops, with the exception of Bali province, though sale was allowed in supermarkets, restaurants, bars, clubs and hotels.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, in more cosmopolitan Indonesian cities like Jakarta, Medan and Surabaya, and also in tourism hotspots such as Bali, Yogyakarta and Batam, alcoholic beverages are readily available, yet with higher prices, owing to the high tax applied upon alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2016, Indonesian Malt Beverage Producers Association (GIMMI) called the House of Representatives to draft for comprehensive regulations on the chain of production and the marketing of alcoholic beverages, instead of total prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since ancient times, local alcoholic beverages were developed by natives in the archipelago.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some panels in 9th century Borobudur bas-reliefs depicted drink vendors, *warung* (small restaurant), and there is a panel depicting a building with people drinking (possibly alcoholic beverages), dancing and having fun, seeming to depict a tavern or lodging house.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to a Chinese source, Yingya Shenglan (c.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] 15th century) the people of Java in Majapahit kingdom drank wine made from palm sap called *tuak* (palm wine).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, by the 16th century Islam began to supplant Hinduism and Buddhism as the major religion in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since then, as a Muslim-majority country, Indonesian Muslims share Islamic dietary laws that prohibit alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, the local alcohol-drinking culture still survives, at least among less-religious members of society and among the non-Muslim community.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Certain ethno-cultural regions which are predominantly Christian are known for their affinity to alcohol-drinking traditions; such as the Batak, Torajan, Minahasan, Ambonese and Papuan.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia has its own traditional alcoholic beverages prepared by fermenting rice grain, gluten, sugar palm sap, and coconuts.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to culinary expert William Wongso, the culture of drinking distilled alcohol was never strong in Indonesia, with only a few regions having developed it.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Batak community in North Sumatra, *tuak* (palm liquor) is a compulsory drink in the celebrations and became a tradition in the community.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Batak tribes are predominantly of Christian Protestant faith, yet some of its clans are Muslim.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] A traditional Batak bar serving *tuak* is called a *lapo tuak*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Toraja lands of South Sulawesi, their version of *tuak* — made from fermented sugar palm sap, is called *ballo*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Torajan traditional ceremonies, rituals and celebrations, *ballo* is always served, either as a prerequisite for the ritual; as an offering for ancestral spirits, as well as for drinks for guests.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Ballo* is also commonly consumed by the neighboring Bugis ethnic group.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Minahasa region of North Sulawesi, an almost identical palm liquor, also made from sugar palm sap, is called *saguer*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Nusa Tenggara and Maluku Islands the people also drink palm wine, locally known as *sopi*.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in the Minahasa region, the people drink a highly alcoholic drink called *cap tikus* (lit.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Cap tikus* is made from distilled *saguer* or *sopi* (palm wine), which increases its alcohol content.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The origin of *cap tikus* brand is unclear.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is suggested that circa 1820s, prior to the 1830 Java War, the KNIL Minahasan legion found and bought distilled *saguer* or *sopi* sold in blue bottles embossed with the image of mouse sold by a Chinese merchant in Fort Amsterdam in Manado.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Today however, because of poor regulation on alcohol production in this region, this traditional home-made *cap tikus* industry is considered as an illegal beverage, due to the high prevalence of mortal alcohol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bottled *brem bali* (Balinese rice wine) and *arrack* are popular beverages in the Hindu-majority island of Bali.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem* is a brownish colored liquor with 5% alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] For Balinese people it has a religious significance too.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem*, *arak* and *tuak* are required for *tabuhan* (offerings) to the gods.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Solo, Central Java, *ciu*, a local adaptation of Chinese wine, made from cider molasses of sugarcane is well known.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is linked to Solo's history as a sugar plantation and production center in colonial times.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Dutch Colonial state was established in Indonesia in the 1800s.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The colonial Dutch brought their European drinking culture to the East Indies, most prominently with beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Heineken beer company established its brewery factory in Surabaya in 1929 during the Dutch colonial rule of Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] By the 1960s, Indonesians developed their own local brands of beer, which included Bintang Beer (nationalized from Heineken) and Anker Beer.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In April 2019, the East Nusa Tenggara provincial government supported the legal aspect of production and distribution of sopi, a local traditional alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] This policy is very likely to make sopi the first fully supported alcoholic product by the local government in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] A Presidential regulation signed by Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono in 2013 gave legal cover to distribution of alcohol, it classified alcoholic beverages in Indonesia in three categories.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Drinks having an alcohol percentage less than 5% (A class), 5%–20% (B class) and more than 20% (C class).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] It was replacement of the 1997 decree after the Supreme Court abolished it following appeals from hard-line religious groups like the Islamic Defenders Front.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The 2012 court ruling came after a draft bill proposed by the United Development Party (PPP) to completely ban the sale, production and consumption of alcohol in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, the 2013 presidential regulation was welcomed by travel agencies in the wake of the harmful effects of the proposed draft on tourism.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Prices of wine and spirits in Indonesia increased by 140.5% and 154.4% respectively between 2009 and 2014.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2015 the government further hiked the import tariff on wine and spirits which nearly doubled the price of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some foreign companies which sell alcohol in Indonesia are Diageo, Pernod Ricard, Remy Cointreau and Bacardi.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] PT Multi Bintang is the largest domestic brewery of Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] As per market experts, because of various regulations, alcohol sales are declining in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bintang Beer of Multi Bintang brewery is the largest selling beer of Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Multi Bintang is a subsidiary of Heineken Asia Pacific.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2011, Bintang Beer won the Gold Medal for the Lager Beer Category and was awarded 'Champion Beer 2011' at the world's class beer competition, the Brewing Industry International Award (BIIA 2011) in London.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2014 Bintang Radler was introduced which was the first flavored beer produced domestically in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other major beer producers are Delta Djakarta known for its Anker Beer, and PT Bali Hai Brewery Indonesia known for its Bali Hai.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia also produces other brands, including San Miguel Beer and Asahi beer, under license.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Diageo manufactures Smirnoff and Captain Morgan products in Bali, which qualifies both brands for classification as locally produced spirits.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The high prices of alcohol beverages in Indonesia, caused by high taxation and restrictions, has led to cases of illegal alcohol in the country.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] As the legal and imported alcoholic beverages become unaffordable, locals turn to illegal bootlegged alcohol for a cheaper drink.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illegal alcoholic drinks are known in Indonesian as *alkohol oplosan* (lit.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] "solved alcohol") and account for over 80% of the alcohol consumed in Indonesia.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illicitly produced liquors which are traditionally home-made, are considered illegal by Indonesian law, due to the high incidence of deadly alcohol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The *lapen* liquor from Yogyakarta for example, is made from industrial alcohol of 85% volume mixed with water with a 1:4 or 5 alcohol to water ratio; then mixed with fruit essence as a flavoring agent.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2010, 16 people died and 5 *lapen* sellers were arrested in Yogyakarta, due to alcohol poisoning and illicit alcohol production.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In September 2010, three Russian Sukhoi fighter technicians died in Makassar from methanol poisoning in their drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Yogyakarta residents were again affected by badly made alcohol in 2016.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other traditionally made alcoholic spirits such as Solo's *ciu*, Manado's *cap tikus*, and some Balinese *arrack* are known as illegal alcohol, also due to the high incidence of alcohol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] This statistic includes all vehicular collisions (including bicycle and motorcycle) in which any alcohol has been consumed, or believed to have been consumed, by the driver, a passenger or a pedestrian associated with the incident.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Thus, if a person who has consumed alcohol and has stopped for a red light is rear-ended by a completely sober but inattentive driver, the incident is listed as alcohol-related, although alcohol had nothing to do with causing the collision.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Furthermore, if a sober motorist hits a drunk pedestrian, the incident is also listed as alcohol-related.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Alcohol-related collisions are often mistakenly confused with alcohol-caused collisions.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Some have criticized the NHTSA for compiling this statistic since it may give the impression that drunk drivers cause a much higher percentage of collisions and does not accurately reflect the problem of drunk driving in the United States.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Nationally, 12.8% of all drivers involved in fatal collisions during 2013 are known to have been intoxicated according to the blood alcohol concentration (BAC laws) of their state.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] This number is based on a systematic examination of the official records of every incident involving a fatality during that year in the US.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] However, a majority of fatalities resulting from car crashes involving alcohol are from sober drivers who are hit by drunk drivers.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] The higher number (about 40%) commonly reported refers to collisions defined as alcohol-related as estimated by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Each year, The Century Council, a national non-profit organization funded by a group of alcohol manufacturers, compiles a document of alcohol-related traffic fatalities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Between 1991 and 2013, the rate of alcohol-related traffic fatalities (ARTF) per 100,000 population has decreased 52% nationally, and 79% among youth under 21.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] According to NHTSA, the 50 US states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico all have BAC limits of 0.08 g/dL or lower.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] In 2016, in the USA, 10,497 people were killed in crashes involving alcohol-impaired drivers; this represents 28 percent of all traffic-related fatalities.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Sixty-two percent of the people killed in such a crash were drivers, 29% occupants, and 9% non-occupants.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] In 2016, the states with the fewest fatalities due to alcohol-impaired drivers were Utah and Mississippi, with 128 and 52 killed (19%).
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Among drivers with BAC levels of 0.08% or higher involved in fatal crashes, 75% are aged between 21 and 44.
[src:alcohol-in-indonesia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Of all motorcyclists killed in crashes, 25% had BACs of 0.08% or greater.
